Building an image classifier with fast.ai

Exploring important concepts in AI (transfer learning, data augmentation, train-test-validation split) by building a simple dogs vs cats image classifier.

Aug 29, 2021 â€¢ 13 min read

deep learning   transfer learning   image classification

Hi there! Today, I would like to illustrate some essential deep learning concepts by going through the process of building a simple image classifier. What is the difference between a validation and test dataset? What exactly is transfer learning (and why is it so powerful)? What is data augmentation? Through this post, I hope to shed some light on some of these important ideas! Equally importantly, I hope to demonstrate that you can get good results without expensive GPUs (everything can be run on a free Google Colab notebook) or huge datasets (I will be using a publicly available dataset on the competition platform Kaggle). Deep learning is a powerful tool that anyone can learn to harness - let's get coding!

In this exercise, I will be building a simple dogs vs cats image classifier. This may seem like a relatively inane task. But we can imagine how these models can be adapted for far-reaching applications - for instance in image classification for X-Ray scans, allowing medical professionals to quickly detect anomalies. Image classification is also extremely flexible - here's an article on how sound waves can be turned into spectrograms and fed into an image classification model.

Technologies

Everything is run on Google Colab which gives you free access to GPUs and is run in a Jupyter-like environment. I will also be using the fast.ai library, which is designed to make deep learning much simpler and more powerful for practicioners. This blogpost follows fastai's "Practical Deep Learning for Coders" course (Lectures 2&3).

We can use the DataBlock API of fast.ai. A datablock is essentially a blueprint on how to assemble your data. It comprises five components:

1) What kind of data are we working with?

This is captured by "blocks=(ImageBlock, CategoryBlock)". The first block in the tuple is the input block, while the second block is the target block. In this case, the image is the input, and the image label (whether it is a dog or cat) is the actual target.

2) How to get the list of items?

This is captured by "get_items=get_image_files". get_image_files is a function which grabs the data from the specified path (in this case, we have defined the path to be the GDrive folder with our pictures inside)

3) How to label those items?

If you download the training dataset and unzip it, you will realise that the first 3 characters of the file name tells us whether its a dog or a cat. We can thus easily infer the label of the training datapoint.

4) How to create the validation set?

This is captured by "splitter=RandomSplitter(valid_pct=0.2, seed=42)". We randomly split the dataset such that 20% of it is used for validation and 80% of it is used for training. By setting the random seed value to be a fixed constant (42), we ensure that the dataset will always be split the same way every time we run the DataBlock API. This is useful in helping us compare the validation metric performance between different models.

5) How to resize the dataset?

This is captured by "item_tfms=Resize(128)". It is important to resize our images so that they are of the same size. This is because we pass small batches of images into our model (instead of one image at a time). As such, we need to make sure that all the images are of the same size. In this implementation, we resize our images to a dimension of 128x128 pixels.

What is the difference between the training, validation, and test datasets?

Great question! This is an important question that can leave many people confused. The training dataset is used to fit the model's parameters. However, if we train the model for a long time, we may run into the issue of overfitting - the neural network essentially "memorizes" the training data such that it can make perfect predictions there, but performs very poorly on unseen data.

That's where the validation dataset comes in. After training the model, we validate it against the validation dataset (using a metric we care about - for instance, accuracy of image classifications). This ensures that our model is indeed generalizable to unseen data (and is not simply overfitting on the training data).

However, the model uses the validation results to tune its hyperparameters. This means that the model will also see the validation data and may overfit on it too. As one final check, we run the model on the test dataset - a completely unseen dataset that acts as the final arbiter of the model's performance.

Here is a good explanation on the difference between model parameters and hyperparameters.

def label_func(fname):
    return "cat" if fname.name[0:3] == "cat" else "dog"

dogs = DataBlock(
    blocks=(ImageBlock, CategoryBlock),
    get_items=get_image_files,
    splitter=RandomSplitter(valid_pct=0.2, seed=42),
    get_y=label_func,
    item_tfms=Resize(128))

Now, we will create a DataLoader which is a special class that allows us to manage our dataset. DataLoader can be used to iterate through the data, manage batches, transform the data, and much more. To create a DataLoader, we need to pass in the blueprints for assembling the data (DataBlock) and where we can find the data (path/"train").

dls = dogs.dataloaders(path/"train")

Data Augmentation

In the cell below, we do a simple form of data augmentation. By using "aug_transforms", we create random variations of the image by altering the angle of the object, level of brightness, etc. This allows the the model to better generalize. Intuitively, by training the model on different variations of the same picture, the model starts to learn about how a cat/dog fundamentally looks like. In contrast, if the model is only trained on brightly lit dog pictures, it will only know how brightly lit dogs look like, and may underperform in low light conditions.

This has important practical applications. Let's say that there has been a series of dog attacks and we want to install a surveilliance system which will warn people of an incoming dog. If we train the model on dog images found on Google, chances are that we will be training our model on well-lighted and curated dog pictures. But in reality, dogs will look different on camera - whether it is due to different lighting conditions or the dog approaching at different angles.

dogs = dogs.new(item_tfms=Resize(128), batch_tfms=aug_transforms(mult=1))
dls = dogs.dataloaders(path/"train")
dls.train.show_batch(max_n=8, nrows=2, unique=True)

Transfer Learning

In the cell below, I am performing transfer learning. Transfer learning is the process of adapting a pre-trained model for a task that it was not originally trained for. There are lots of fantastic pre-trained models out there - models which have been trained on large amounts of data and have proven to be effective for a wide variety of tasks. It is far better to build on these great baseline models, rather than create something completely from scratch.

In this case, we use the ResNet model, a pre-trained model with proven success for a wide variety of image classification tasks. The 18 indicates that I am using the version with 18 layers. ResNet18 was trained on >1 million images from the ImageNet database. It can classify images into 1000 object categories (from animals to people to household objects) and has thus learned rich feature representations for a wide variety of categories.

To customize this pre-trained model for our specific use case (dogs vs cats), we need to fine tune the model. Fine-tuning generally involves three steps:

1) Firstly, we remove the last layer of the pre-trained ResNet model. This last layer is always specially customized to the original task of the pre-trained model. Thus, we replace that last layer with one or more layers of our own. These layers are initialized with randomised parameters. We call these layers the "head".

2) Secondly, we use one epoch to train this new head, ensuring that is customized for our specific use case. One epoch passes when the model looks at every single image once.

3) Finally, we use the total number of epochs requested (in our example, this is 3) to re-fit the entire model. However, we will be updating the parameters of the later layers faster than that of the earlier layers. Intuitively, you can think of the earlier layers of the ResNet model as capturing fundamental patterns and relationships (for instance, edge and colour detection). These fundamental patterns are crucial for any image classification problem. As such, we are quite happy to keep these layers relatively intact.

On the other hand, the later layers start to capture patterns and relationships that are more customized for the original use case. For instance, the ResNet model was designed to classify images into 1000 categories. The later layers may thus capture patterns and relationships customized for different categories (e.g. the texture of the tree bark for tree classification). These aren't useful for classifying dogs vs cats, and so we update the parameters more liberally.

learn = cnn_learner(dls, resnet18, metrics=error_rate) #Error rate is the metric we are trying to optimize for
learn.fine_tune(3)

Confusion Matrix

A confusion matrix is a great way of understanding how our model performed on the validation or test datasets. The diagonal values represent accurate predictions, while the off-diagonal values represent misses. For instance, we can see that in our validation dataset, we correctly identified 2482 cats as cats, but mistook 48 cats for being dogs.

Confusion matrices offer a higher degree of granularity than a simple error rate. They allow us to zoom in on how our model worked for individual categories. This can be extremely useful in the case of class imbalance. Consider a credit card fraud detector. Most of the transactions in the training dataset should be "clean", while a tiny proportion is fraudulent. If we are not careful, training our model on such imbalanced data may result in a model that always predicts the "clean" label. When testing this model on an unseen dataset, we may get an extremely good error rate. The model always predicts "clean", and only a tiny proportion of the datapoints are fraudulent. As such, the overall error rate is going to be very low. However, if we examine the confusion matrix, we will realise that we are misclassifying all the fraudulent cases as "clean" - this means that our model has failed to actually detecting fraud!

interp = ClassificationInterpretation.from_learner(learn)
interp.plot_confusion_matrix()

Model post-mortem

We can pull out the images in the validation dataset that we wrongly classified or were not confident about. This can give some insight on where our model may be underperforming. For instance, we may realise that our model is doing badly on poorly lit pictures. In contrast, we may even realise that certain pictures in our validation dataset were incorrectly labelled. By doing this simple analysis, we can identify ways in which we can improve our model before running it against the final test dataset.

In the cell below, each image is labeled with four things: prediction, actual label, loss, and probability. The probability here is the confidence level, from zero to one, that the model has assigned to its prediction:

interp.plot_top_losses(5, nrows=1)

We can see that our model may be underperforming on pictures in which the animal is seen from an uncommon angle (e.g. top-down) or if the resolution is poor. To circumvent this issue, we may want to expand our training dataset with more angles/lower-res photos. Alternatively, we can create greater variations through data augmentation. Once we are happy with the model, we can start to test it against a completely unseen test dataset.

Summary

By building an image classifier, I hoped to illustrate a few deep learning concepts. Here is a quick summary:

1) Training vs Validation vs Test data: The training data is used to fit the model's parameters. To avoid overfitting on the training data, we use the validation data to evaluate the model's performance during training. The test data is used as the final arbiter of the model's performance.

2) Data Augmentation: Creating random variations of the same picture (e.g. different angles, brightness). This allows the model to learn fundamental characteristics about the object, improving its ability to generalize.

3) Transfer Learning: Transfer learning is the process of adapting a pre-trained model for a task that it was not originally trained for. This allows us to leverage extremely powerful models to achieve excellent results for our specific use case.
